column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On Monday, August 1, 2011 I was called about 0840 on a possible leaking tank car of Ethanol at Gambrinus yard, car number UTLX 211157 on 10 track.  I went to investigate the leaking car and found that product was coming from the protective relief device when the car was moved.  I called Chemtrec at 0909 hrs to notify shipper and report the leak.  They gave me report #2011020200041.  Darren Smith from the shipper, Aventine, called at 0921 to ask what the problem was and I told him and he said to call the contractor of our choice to handle the problem.  I called SunPro at 0943 to come see if maybe the O rings needed replaced in the PRD.  I then called Don McDonald of the Stark LEPC at 1030 just to let him know what was going on and that we didn’t need his assistance.  SunPro arrived at 1030 and after we investigated, we found that the top portion of the valve could be operated up and down by hand meaning that the interior spring of the device had broken.   We removed from the breadbox seal #0261043 and replaced with seal #486.  We removed from the manway cover seal #0261044 and it also had writing on the back which said LS1112 and we replaced this seal with #475.   I called Roger Spring at Marathon to see if they would receive the car for offloading so we didn’t have to transfer it.  He said he would call the Canton plant to see.  He asked that I call the FRA to see if it would be ok to make that move.  I spoke to the FRA in Washington adn they said we could make that move providing that wedge the PRD shut so it wouldn’t open in transit so could it could  move into the refinery for offloading. The pressure relief device will be replaced by UTLX on the repair track at the refinery and then a movement approval will be gotten so the car to move to the UTLX home shop on Marion, Ohio.

FRA Hazmat inspector Tim Rowan, while performing routine inspection at Buffalo & Pittsburgh Railroad, Falls Creek Yard observied a slight leak at the outlet valve cap plug of tank car, GATX 82016.  Outlet cap plug was slightly wet.  Car inspector was notified of leak and tighten outlet cap plug.  Car inspector determined as well as inspector Rowan that the leak had stopped.    Per FRA authority the car was moved that evening into the Rescar repair facility which is located less than one mile from where the defective car was discovered.

customer checked in at ticket counter and checked in container. reservation had authorization to transport Dewar container with liquid nitrogen. Baggage handler placed container on bag belt and either didn't acknowledge or ignored arrows to keep container upright. container was on its side and moving on bag belt. Agent Rosas turned toward bag belt to see fog like smoke eminating from container and saw a liquid dripping onto the bag belt. She stopped the belt and agent Pena came over to lift the container upright. Both agents contacted the CSM Matt Pawlyk to address the situation. Mr. Pawlyk spoke to the customer about contents, notified Env. Coord. E.Curiel to assess the container and the residual of a small frozen patch on the bag belt. Mr. Pawlyk contacted the SAC desk to advise of the spill and receive instructions to refuse the container for shipment due to being unable to guarantee the shipment could remain upright for its trip to Brazil. Mr. Pawlyk observed the internal cylinder top was loose and leaking. He advised customer that it was improperly packaged and unacceptable in its present state. Photos were taken of the container and the residual spot on the belt.
column169: contacted baggage handler supervisor to review baggage handling procedures with the employee. Notified Passenger Service manager to post a notice to review proper handling procedures of containers with markings.

column168: A Clean Harbor's driver was conducting a routine walk around inspection when he noticed that a small amount of material was leaking from the level gauge of his vacuum tanker. The driver immediatly applied vacuum to the tanker in order to stop the leak and used sorbent pads to wipe the tanker of the leaked material. The driver then contacted his home dispatcher to request a repair. A local response company was contracted (HEPACO Environmental)and dispatched to the scene for repair of the leaking gauge. Repairs were completed and the tanker continued transport to its intended disposal facility. Tennessee Dept of Environment was notified of the incident.
column169: At the time the tanker was loaded for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. The gauge was repaired by the repair responder.

column168: This shipment arrived in Ketchikan as a one pc. shipment labeled electrical wire.  The top two small boxes taped on top had statements that said "US DOT: THIS PACKAGE CONFORMS TO 49CFR 173.4 FOR DOMESTIC HIGHTWAY OR RAIL TRANSPORT ONLY.  Ketchikan customer service manager was called to air freight office and took pictures of the outside of the boxes, and then the wharehouse agent opened the boxes.  There were 2 small cans inside each box, labeled Cable Cleaning Preparation Kit, that advised they contain combustible liquid and vapor.  The  cans do not have any weights on the outside,but do not weigh more than 6oz each.  They say contains:Isoparaffnic Hydrocarbon(6472-48-9) d-imonene (5889-27-5).  They also contain 2 tubes of rubber adhesive  .5fl oz that are marked extremely flammable, and labeled petroleum distilate (64724-88-7)A: Methyl Ethyl Keytone (78-93-3): Polychloroprene (9010-98-4): Magnesium Resinate (68611-24-5) Toulene (108-88-3).  There was no release of any substance, and we are holding this shipment for inspection and release by the FAA.  Photos of the boxes are attached.
column169: I think we need to go back to the acceptance agent in Portland and advise that any time there is a transport statement on a box, or un markings of any kind, we need to take a closer look at that box to make sure that it does not contain any undeclared hazardous materials.

column168: On 08/01/2011 at 1222 hours personnel in the Patio Yard, Winchester KY, discovered   ECUX 459004, a loaded tank car of Methyl Ethyl Ketone, leaking liquid from the bottom of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper ExxonMobil Chemical Company was notified thru CHEMTREC # 2011-08-01-00149. Pettit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from the bottom outlet cap. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper representative. Pettit Environmental removed the cap, checked for leaks, replaced the cap and tightened it with a 36 pipe wrench. The leak was secured and the car was released to transportation.     This incident did require a special switch move.  No 7.1 will be required for this incident    A charge for switching the car is required.    NARRI Cause Code: 149 / 5     NARRI Index: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: At 1430 hours on Friday, August 12, 2011, PTRA Traimaster Reynolds was notified that there was a strong odor coming from tank car GATX 94698 in track 20 at the PTRA Manchester Yard. U.S. Environmental Services was notified of the vapor leak and responded to the scene. They arrived at 1515 hours and inspected the car. They determined that the vapors were leaking from the manway area on account of an old deteriorated and torn gasket. There was a three inch tear in the gasket and significant age releated wear around the gasket edge. USES installed a new gasket and re-sealed the tank car for transport.  The scene was cleared at 1610 hours.
column169: Odfjell Operations Superintendent Pat Mentzel was notified at 1510 on Friday, August 12, 2011. He is investigating the cause of the failure and will advise handling and steps to prevent future NARs.

column168: Yard crew was switching an in bound train and noticed the leak.  the crew moved the car to a safe location for the leak to be repaired.
column169: As a transportation company we will continue with our training program to ensure that each crew reacts the same as the yard crew did to recognize danger and  proper reaction to it.

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. arrived at the Clackamas OR facility for transfer of waste to its intended disposal destination. During offloading the drum was dropped on its side causing the containers top to come off and spill product. Response personnel cleaned up spillage donning the proper PPE and placed the container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris for continued transportation. All required local and state notifications were made. Oregon DEC Report#2011-1935
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. Offloading employee is recieving additional training.  In addition, Clean Harbors spoke with the customer regarding this incident and they were also concerned that there was some liquid in the waste product shipped by their employees. They held a training session with their crew regarding proper container selection, UN ratings, and what material is acceptable in what type of container. They said they will do whatever is necessary to ensure we do not have a repeat of this occurrence.

column168: Tank car UTLX 201765 in the railyard was reported with fresh product on its side shell that emanated from its manway closure. No ground impact from this product release was evident. BNSF inspection of UTLX 201765 revealed all manway securement bolts were tool tight and the shipper seal on the manway lid was intact.  On Monday, 8/15/2011, the nearby loader of UTLX 201765 was notified to secure the manway closure and clean the product spillage off the tank shell. Responders found the manway gasket was missing and a new manway gasket was installed. Afterwards, the manway securement bolts were tool tightened. Non-evaporated spillage and product staining were remediated. The manway cover was resealed with seal numbered 2156449.

column168: DRIVER PULLED OVER TO USE THE RESTROOM AT THE TRUCK STOP WHEN HE NOTICED HIS TRAILER WAS LEAKING. THE TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT WAS ISOLATED IN THE PACKING LOT. A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CONTACTED TO ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP. THE ER COMPANY ARRIVED AND PH'D THE LEAKING PRODUCT AND DETERMINED IT WAS A CORROSIVE. THE CREW CONTAINED THE RELEASED LIQUID ON THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA AND PROCEEDED TO SORT THROUGH THE SHIPPING PAPERS TO NARROW DOWN THE SEARCH FOR THE LEAKING PRODUCT.    THE CREW DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PPE AND ENTERED THE TRAILER. THE CREW LOCATED A PALLET OF CLOTHESLINE FRESH BLD (2) THAT HAD LYED OVER DUE TO A LOAD SHIFT. THE PALLET CONTAINED INDIVIDUAL 5 GALLON PAILS THAT WERE SHRINK WRAPPED AND NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED. THE CREW REMOVED THE SHRINK WRAP AND SORTED THROUGH THE PAIL TO LOCATE 3-5 GALLON PAILS AT THE BOTTOM OF THE STACK THAT HAD BEEN CRUSHED DURING THE LOAD SHIFT CAUSING THE PAIL TO BE DAMAGED AND RELEASE THEIR CONTENTS. THE CREW STATED TWO OF THE PAILS HAD BEEN CRUSHED TO AN EXTENT THAT THE BOTTOMS OF THE PAILS HAD BEEN CREAED BY THE FORCE AGAINST THE PALLET ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO POUR OUT. THE THIRD AND LAST REMAINING PAIL WAS ALSO CRUSHED CAUSING GREAT PRESSURE TO THE SIDE OF THE PAIL WHICH CAUSED THE RECESSED POUR SPOUT TO POP OUT AND RELEASE THE PRODUCT.    THE CREW REMOVED THE THREE EMPTY PAILS, WIPED THE TRAILER FLOOR AND REMAINING CARGO CLEAN. THE CREW RESTACKED THE REMAINING 5 GALLON PAILS ON THE PALLET AND SECURED THEM WITH PLYWOOD AND PACKING MEDIA TO PREVENT SHIFTING DURING TRANSPORTATON.    THE CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS CONTAINERIZED INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM ALONG WITH THE EMPLYDRUMS WHICH WERE LABELED AND RMOVED FROM THE SITE FOR LATER DISPOSAL.    A TOTAL OF 15 GALLON OF INDUSTRIAL GRAGE SOAP HAD BEEN RELEASED.

Tank car GATX 7729 was reported expelling product vapor/mist from the top fitting area during normal switching operations in the railyard. GATX 7729 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 7729 and determined that the frangible disc in the safety vent had ruptured. The nearby shipper was notified. The shipper responder confirmed that the 165 psig frangible disc within the Salco Quick Inspect safety vent had ruptured. Also, the top Quick Inspect body of the safety vent system appeared damaged. A new Salco Quick Inspect safety vent with frangible disc was procured and installed on 8/04/2011. Spillage on GATX 7729 was neutralized. No ground impact from spillage was observed.

Suttles picked up loaded trailer at BASF in Geismar, LA and proceeded to customer.  At the scalehouse on I-12 at Hammond, LA, westbound unit was selected to undergo a DOT Roadside inspection. In the course of the inspection a small amount of product was noted in the dome box of the trailer.  Suttles personnel from the St. Gabriel, LA facility were dispatched to the scene where the dome gasket was replaced under this auspices of a LA. State Police Hazmat Officer.  The small amount of product in the box was removed by wiping with a rag.  The soiled rag was decontaminated and disposed of at the St Gabriel facility.  The unit was allowed to proceed to destination without further incident.

column168: I WAS LOADING AS USUAL FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEDURE MY TRUCK WAS LOADED (208) TO WHERE I NEEDED IT TO BE IN THE FRONT TANK THE PUP (776) WAS FILLING UP GETTING CLOSE TO WHAT I CONSIDERED ALMOST BEING DONE AND I DECIDED TO GO UP THE STAIRS ON THE CATWALK TO GAUGE THE LEVEL OF THE TANK. I FIGURED I HAD PLENTY OF ROOM TO LOAD THE REST OF THE OIL NEEDED AND STILL HAVE ROOM FOR EXPANSION AS NEEDED, WHILE ON THE CATWALK I HEARD ANOTHER EMPLOYEE YELL AT ME. I RAN DOWN THE STAIRS AND ACKNOWLEDGED THE PUP WAS FLOWING OVER AND OIL WAS SPILLING ON THE GROUND. I QUICKLY WENT TO REVERSE THE PUMP ON THE TRUCK TO KEEP IT FROM PULLING MORE OIL ONTO THE PUP. THEN I PLACED A FIVE GALLON BUCKET UNDER THE SIDE OF THE PUP BUT BY THIS TIME THERE WAS 5 LESS BBLS ALREADY ON THE GROUND. THERE WAS A WATER TRUCK PULLING UP ON LOCATION SO I HAD HIM PULL THE OIL OFF THE GROUND THAT HAD PUDDLED UP. I THEN CALLED DISPATCH AND DAVE RADEL TO INFORM THEM OF WHAT HAD HAPPENED. THE SPILL WAS KEPT TO A MINIUM AS BEST AS POSSIBLE. I WAS DRUG TESTED AND ALCOHOL TESTED AND HAD DAVE R AND ENCANA'S SAFETY WITNESS. I WAS NEGATIVE AND OK TO OPERATE MY TRUCK AGAIN. WHEN THE INCIDENT HAPPENED I WAS DRIVING A TRUCK THAT IS NOT MY ASSIGNED TRUCK AND THE PUP IS APPARENTLY SMALLER THAN THE ONE I NORMALLY PULL, SO THAT I BELIEVE WAS A MAIN FACTOR FOR THE SPILL. I WAS LOADING A LEGAL LOAD BECAUSE I HAD TO GO ACROSS SCALES. I DIDN'T DO ANYTHING DIFFERENT THAN I NORMALLY DO BUT DIDN'T ACKNOWLEDGE HOW MUCH SMALLER THE PUP IS. I HAD NOT HAD ANY PROBLEMS WHEN LOADING ALL THE OTHER TIMES, AND WAS FOLLOWING MY SAME PROCEDURE. I STOOD OUTSIDE THE TRUCK AND CHECKED ON MY GAUGES THE WHOLE TIME JUST MISJUDGED TOWARDS THE END HOW MUCH ROOM I HAD LEFT.

At a Central Transport terminal, a drum of product was found to be leaking.  The terminal personnel moved the trailer across the parking lot.  Approximately 30 gallons of product was found to be released inside the trailer and onto the asphalt parking lot.  Also, a catch basin was impacted at the loading the dock.  An environmental contractor, Environmental Restoration, arrived on site for cleanup.  The overpacked the leaking drum and collect the released product from the trailer floor, parking area, and catch basin.
Per supervisor's report ~ driver failed to open the header valve before unloading product ~ causing the gasket & hose to blow out ~ resulted in a spill of approx. 26 gallons of crude oil ~

Tank car NATX 72579 was reported emanating a product odor in the railyard. NATX 72579 was then cordoned-off in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected NATX 72579. The responders reported finding the closure plug on the vapor valve (VV) not in a tool tight condition with this valve in the closed position. The responder's tool tightened the VV closure plug three full turns until tool tight. Afterwards, the residue product vapor/odor dissipated and ceased. Intact seal numbered 0561569 that was removed from the valve housing cover was replaced with seal BNSF 320728. Response was concluded by 0200 hrs. PDT, 8/15/2011.  The side specification stencil on NATX 72579 indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2001 and next due in 2011.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car UTLX 210295 was reported sloshing product from its manway closure during normal switching activities in the railyard. Movement was stopped and a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected UTLX 210295. The responder reported that 2 of 8 manway securement bolts were not applied (hanging) and the remaining 6 securement bolts were less than tool tight. The responder properly secured all manway securement bolts. Afterwards, UTLX 210295 was moved and the responder observed product still sloshing out from the manway closure which is indicative of a manway gasket not sealing properly. Movement of UTLX 5210295 was stopped again and with the assistance from another BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder, the condition of the manway gasket was inspected. The fiber manway gasket installed was found compressed thus losing its sealing ability. A new manway gasket was installed and the responders properly resecured the manway closure. No further product release was observed from subsequent movements of UTLX 210295 in the railyard. All spillage evaporated. Intact manway closure seal numbered 1467248 was replaced by seal BNSF 06157608.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A Schneider Onsite Safety Representative called in to our support shift team and advised he saw trl 28477 leaking product out of the pressure release valve and the drain tube. Shannon Schick (Hazmat Manager) and Steve Torres (Bulk Safety Director) were immediately notified.  It was quickly determined that product was loaded on a wrong trailer type (corrosive product & aluminum trailer) and was having a slow reaction that would slowly build pressure and release product and vapors every couple of minutes through the pressure vent when it reached 30 psi. The vent itself had no failure but it was the selected choice a few screens back as nothing else seemed to fit any closer.  We cleared out our tankwash personnel and then had the trailer brought into the wash bay which had ample containment for any uncontained releases.  Roughly 5 gallons had spilled out from the dome before we were able to get it in our tankwash bay.  Chemtrec and the Louisiana State Police were then notified.      Chemtrec - 20110825000008  State Police Reporting - 11-05182    The ER Contractor we hired (EH&S care of ERTS)arrived on scene and was briefed.  We used the exisiting pressure on the trailer to bring it to neutral atmoshphere before opening the air inlet to proceed with using a pump for the product transfer.  Opening the air inlet was to ensure we didnt collapse the trailer while performing the pump unload.  When the transfer was complete the contractor then used soda ash to neutralize the material and absorbants.  The area outside was excavated and removed from site.  I put in the value of product on the prior screen assuming the product is not usable after going through the reaction.  I also entered the current trailer value (if we are going to scrap it) but we are still trying to determine whether the trailer will be fixable enough to use for training purposes.
column169: 1. The computer system we are using does not automatically flag corrosive materials to not be able to load in aluminum trailers.  Now a report is being generated daily & our IT Department will be entering trailer requirements for any corrosive commodity that does not have the right requirements associated to it.    2. Trailer numbering sequence.  All of our older aluminum trailer were under 202 numbers (ex - 20292, 20295, etc).  Our new aluminum trailers are under a numbering sequence such as (28477, 28095,etc) which is consistent with the numbering for our stainless steel insulated trailers.  The numbering system for our aluminum trailers will recieve a new numbering sequence to help eliminated confusion    3.  Driver and shipper did not see the sign on the side of the trailer that says do not load

column168: Intermodal container MEDU 412126, entrained on an inbound BNSF intermodal train, was reported emanating a strong 'ammonia like' odor in the railyard.  The intermodal flatcar that MEDU 412126 was riding atop was setout of the train and isolated on a repair track for further investigation. A crane removed MEDU 412126 from its top double-stacked position and grounded it in an area for responders to open container and investigate the odor source. After removal of all 78 drums inside MEDU 412126, the responders reported finding only one leaking 55 gallon poly drum found towards the front of the container. This drum was punctured by a floor deck nail at its bottom head. This leaking drum was placed inverted into an overpack drum with the nail hole covered, which was then properly labeled and sealed. The interior spillage within MEDU 412126 was neutralized and cleaned. All drums (including the overpack drum with spent cleaning supplies) were returned inside MEDU 412126 properly blocked and braced.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-loading interior inspection of intermodal trailers/containers includes careful examinations for sharp objects that could puncture or compromise packages scheduled to be loaded within.

Driver was returning back from Denver Colorado driving on US 6 Loveland Pass and was entering a left hand curve and was traveling too fast to negotiate the curve and rolled the tractor trailer to the right side of roadway, Trailer skidded striking a concrete barrier causing the body of the tanker to be ripped open spilling approx 2465 gallons onto the right side of the roadway ditch. Some the Dyed Diesel Fuel ran across the street into Clear Creek. Belfor Enviromental was on scene to contain the spill and start cleanup processes. Belfor created dikes and berms to contain the spill and a Vacuum truck was used to suck up the pools of collected diesel. Manual excavation with heavy equipment to mitigate the spill is in use and the cleanup and soil sampling is underway. As for Clear creek skims and booms were used immedaitly to collect any fuel in the waterway.

GLNX 34517's side specification stencil indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2001 and next due in 2011.

column168: Tank car GATX 29543 standing in the railyard was reported leaking product from the top fitting area onto its side shell with no ground impact. A BNSF hazardous material responder immediately inspected GATX 29543 finding the leak source at both reclosing 75 psig pressure relief valves (PRV). The ambient temperatures at this time were at or above 105 degrees F. All spillage was rapidly evaporating. The responder determined that the PRV liquid releases were due to an overfilled (by volume) condition. GATX 29543 was carefully isolated in the railyard for product reduction by contract responders. Product was off-loaded into three 250 gallon sized totes without further incident. The product filled totes were delivered to the nearby consignee for contaminate testing and acceptance. No further product release was observed from GATX 29543 afterwards.

column168: Randy Bunkley, Branch Manager for Allied Universal Corp in Brunswick, received a call from Todd Tucker, V.P. Operations for Allied, at 10:30pm reporting a bleach leak from our railcar # TILX110426 in Waycross, Ga.  Mr Tucker had received his notification from Ed Cook, Hazmat Director for CSX railroad, that a leak was detected around the dome area of the railcar.  Randy arrived at the scene at 12:00am and was escorted to the railcar where the Hazmat crew from SWS Environmental Services was already working on the railcar.  On top of the railcar, tightening the bolts around the dome area, was Larry Hall with CSX.  Larry Hall reported to Randy Bunkley that one(1) out of the four (4) bolts holding down the flange for the dip tube was loose the bleach had spilled out around the bolt and down the side of the railcar onto the ground.  Clean up was completed on the railcar around 2:30am.  It was determined that approximately 3 - 4 gallons of bleach had splashed out the dome.  Allied sent a crew the next morning to wash down the area around the railcar and tracks.

J Peak Propane's bobtail truck loaded with aprox. 2333 gallons of Propane was head southbound on Interstate 15 around 55 mph because the driver was just coming out of construction.  The front tire blewout even though the tread depth was good thus causing the truck to strike another vehicle and the overturn and role.  The other driver was not injured, but the drive of the propane truck hit his head and was transported to a hospital where he received stitches and was later released. The truck barrel lost no propane, one hose failed which lost about 5 gallons of propane.  A hazmat team arrived and closed the freeway for 8 hrs, while they tried to extricate the propane. However this was never accomplished and eventually the truck was turned upright and towed to a wrecking yard.
column169: More driver training on what to do in case of and emergency such as a blowout is going to be implemented in order to mitigate future risk.

On 8/20/11 at 2135 hrs personnel in the CSXT Howell yard discovered UTLX 209997, a loaded tank car of Alcohols NOS, leaking from the bottom outlet valve area. The car was isolated and Archer Daniels Midland, IDEM and the NRC were notified, CHEMTREC report #2011082000131.  Summit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve packing nut to be loose. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Gene Smith 217-451-4212.  Contractor personnel tightened the packing nut at the BOV and cleaned up the spilled material. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. On 08/21/2011 at 0500 hours, personnel in the CSXT Mobile Yard, Siebert Yard, discovered GATX 9561, a residue tank car of DIMETHYLAMINE, ANHYDROUS, leaking from the pressure plate. The car was isolated and the shipper Polychemie Inc., the receiver Taminco Inc., local 911, State Alabama DEM and Chemtrec report # 2011082100007 were notified.  United States Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene along with the CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager and confirmed a vapor leak at the pressure plate, 18 of 22 pressure plate bolts were loose. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Jim Bishop  228-363-2583. Contractor personnel from American Railcar Industries, a Class G shop repaired and re-qualified the rail car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. column168: RESPONDED TO A SPILL AT 2140 ON PD 11.  WEARING PPE IDENTIFIED THE SPILL AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID FROM THE DOT DIAMOND LABEL AND THE HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID PLACED THE SPILL IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND ENSURED THERE WAS NO RESIDUE LEFT BEFORE TRANSPORTING THE LEAKER TO THE REWRAP CENTER.  THE CAUSE OF THE DAMAGE APPEARED TO BE BECAUSE THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN DROPPED, THE GLASS BOTTLES INSIDE THE PACKAGE WERE SHATTERED.  THE DAMAGED PORTION OF THE SPILL WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.  THERE WAS NO SALVAGEABLE PORTION TO BE RETURNED.

WAS CALLED TO PD-9 DOOR 61 AROUND 1:45 AM FOR A HAZMAT SPILL. INSPECTED THE OUTER PACKAGING OF THE BOX: THERE WAS LEAKAGE ON THE OUTSIDE WITH AN 8-PART FORM WITH A DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL FLAMMABLE LIQUID 3.  CARTON HAD PRINTED HEPTANE ON OUTSIDE.  UTILIZING DECISION TREE, OPENED THE PACKAGE TO SEE IF THE LABEL ON THE OUTSIDE WAS THE SAME AS CONTENTS ON THE INSIDE. CONTAINERS WERE SHATTERED, CONTENTS WERE THE SAME.  PACKAGE WAS PUT INTO A SPILL TUB AND WAS PUT ONTO THE SPILL CART TO BE TAKEN BACK TO THE DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  UTILIZING CORRECT FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS RESPONSE SHEET WAS ABLE TO FURTHER PROCESS THE DAMAGED GOODS.

On Monday August 29th, 2011 Edist of Ontario, California tendered to Alaska Airlines airway bill 027-8087-2352. The shipment stated UN3481 Lithium Ion Batteries, Not-restricted, PI 966. When the shipment arrived in Seattle off of Alaska Flight 531/29AUG the shipment was placed on hold due to the Lithium Battery Label was not on the shipment. Later it was discovered that the shipment contained 105 batteries per box. We contacted a hazmat packaging specialist in Seattle to label the shipment correctly and to return to Alaska Air Cargo. The hazmat specialist determined that the shipment was actually UN 3090 and UN 3091 Lithium metal batteries and Lithium metal contained in equipment.

column58: Discharge Valve or Coupling; Discharge Valve or Coupling
column62: Abrasion; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: Driver was waiting at consignee contained offload area for notification to proceed with the transfer from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank when they noticed a drip coming from the discharge valve on the trailer.  The rate was about 2 drips a minute. Driver put a bucket and spill pad under it.  It was determined that there was an issue with the internal and external valve not holding properly.  An emergency response team was called in to stand by and assist with transferring the product to another cargo tank.
column169: A proper visual inspection by the tankwash and then by driver and loading personnel, should have detected the issue with the internal valve not seated properly unless it became misaligned during transit.  It's very unusual to have issues with the internal and external valves.  The trailer was brought into the shop after it was cleaned to be inspected.  There were several nicks on the sealing lid of the external that allowed product to seep through.  The entire assembly was replaced.

column168: Quality Carriers - Claim Number: 31323    On August 14, 2011, a Quality Carriers Tanker stopped at a rest area off of I-80 West, Exit 90 in Elkhart, IN and noticed the dome lid was not secure on the tanker. Due to the unsecure dome lid approximately 5 gallons of UN1866 Formaldehye Resin released onto the asphalt parking lot. No storm drains, waterways or soils were impacted as a result of this release. Quality Carriers contacted ERTS on August 16, 2011 to manage this incident. ERTS dispatched Environmental Management Services to the site to investigate the release further. Environmental Management Services personnel arrived on site and reported that the material had dried to the surface and no additional remediation could be done short of removing the asphalt. ERTS is working with the Indiana Toll Road to determine the best remediation process. ERTS has coordinated with Best Environmental who also investigated the site and will be remediating the area once a plan of action is implemented by the Indiana Toll Road.

column168: THE UNLOADING OPERATOR WAS OPENING UP THE UNLOADING VALVES TO UNLOAD AN AMMONIA CAR. THE HOSE FITTING THAT WAS HOOKED UP TO THE A END LIQUID VALVE ON THE TANK CAR WAS IMPROPERLY ATTACHED.  THE GASKET THAT GOES BETWEEN THE WIND HALF AND THE THREAD HALF OF THE HAMMER FITTING WAS DAMAGED OR MISSING AND DID NOT PROVIDE A GOOD SEAL BETWEEN THE TWO HALF'S OF THE UNION. WHEN THE OPERATOR CRACKED THE UNLOADING VALVE ON THE CAR OPEN, AMMONIA STARTED LEAKING FROM THE HAMMER UNION.  THE OPERATOR EVACUATED THE AREA WITHOUT CLOSING THE VALVE DUE TO THE LEAK. HE THEN CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR TO REPORT THE LEAK. 1. SUPERVISOR ALERTED THE PLANT ENERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. 10:20AM 2. THE PLANT WIDE ALARM SYSTEM WAS ACTIVATED TO LET ALL PLANT PERSONAL KNOW ABOUT THE SITUATION WITH THE AMMONIA LEAK. 3. ALL REQUIRED OUTSIDE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE IMMEDIATELY UPON KNOWING OF THE AMMONIA LEAK. 4. SIMPLOT RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED AND MADE ENTRY IN LEVEL A SUITS.  THEY CLOSED THE VALVE ON THE CAR AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. 11:00AM 5. AFTER WE WERE CLEARED TO ENTER THE AREA WE REMOVED THE LEAKING UNLOADING HOSE AND DISCOVERED THE GASKET WAS MISSING. 6. WE INSTALLED A NEW GASKET IN THE FITTING AND RECONNECTED THE HOSE AND UNLOADED THE CAR WITHOUT ANY FURTHER ISSUES.  NOTE:  THE TANK CAR AND ITS VALVES WERE NEVER THE ISSUE, THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A MISSING GASKET ON OUR UNLOADING HOSE FITTING. THE DURATION OF THE LEAK WAS 40 MINUTES.
column169: THE OPERATOR WAS COUNSELED ABOUT HIS FAILURE TO FOLLOW WRITTEN PROCEDURES REQUIRING HIM TO CHECK FOR A GOOD GASKET IN THE HOSE FITTINGS.  THE SHIFT SUPERVISOR REVIEWED THE STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES WITH THE EMPLOYEE TO MAKE SURE HE UNDERSTOOD WHAT IS EXPECTED OF HIM.  THE EVENT WAS REVIEWED WITH OTHER OPERATING CREWS TRAINED IN UNLOADING OF AMMONIA, AND THEY WERE REMINDED TO MAKE SURE THE FITTINGS, HOSES AND GASKETS ARE IN GOOD CONDITION BEFORE UNLOADING AMMONIA.

column168: A Transfer was being conducted between railcar (UTLX 13923) and a single compartment trailer (23088) with a single  dome. The loader climbed to the top of the railcar to prepare for the transfer shut down. He noticed product spraying form the jumper hose between the Air tee valve and the Product tee valve. The loader closed the product valve. The product was contained inside the track pans, no product contacted the ground. Team members responded immediately and applied soda ash to the spilled product. Clean up material was placed in designated drum and properly marked.
column169: Continue to diligently perform arrival inspections and closely monitor loads in progress. Have placed in practice a policy of using most experienced loaders for sulfuric acid loads.

column168: Driver reported that he had successfully transferred part of the product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He cleared the hose the best he could and thought it was close to empty.  He had to deliver the rest of the load to a different storage tank so he had to disconnect the hose so he could move to the next tank.  When he disconnected it from the trailer, he realized that there was still too much product in the hose to move to the other tank.  He was going to hook the hose back up to the trailer to try to clear it better and in the process of reconnecting, he spilled about 2 gallons of product.  product was flushed to the customer containment system.
column169: Driver is scheduled for performance enhancement training to go over the proper procedures to clear the hose when using a pump.

column168: Loded cargo tank was spotted at our Gary facility awaiting another driver to bring to the consignee for delivery.  A few drips were noticed coming from the skin near the landing gear. Not sure at first if it was product or maybe rainwater in the insulation.   A bucket and spill pad were put underneath.  To err on side of safety, the product was successfully transferred to another cargo tank.
column169: The shop inspected the cargo tank when it was clean and determined that there was a small crack in the barrel allowing product to seep into the insulation and drip out.  The cause of failure (dropped) is only a guess because of the location of the crack.  It's possible that when a driver or tankwash disconnected from the loaded trailer at sometime, the dolly legs may not have been cranked down all the way and it was jarred when the tractor pulled away weakening the barrel.  Drivers are trained in the proper procedure to make sure the dolly legs are down all the way and to ease out slowly. The trailer is lined with Plasite. The crack was repaired and the cargo tank will be sent to Plasite vendor to repair the lining.

column168: Driver reported that when he was transferring product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank, the PVC customer fill-line piping to which he had his transfer hose attached, failed.  Driver was by the trailer control and was able to close the valve immediately minimizing the amount of product spilled. The weight of the attached hose on the possibly weathered piping appears to be the issue.
column169: The customer will install a veritical inlet pipe for future deliveries.  That will minimize the strain of the hose on it.

column168: On August 18, 2011, R&L Carriers contacted ERTS to manage a Corrosive UN2735 release that occured at the R&L Terminal located at 4801 Almonaster Avenue in New Orleans, LA. It was reported that approximately 15 gallons of material released from a 15 gallon plastic drum, which was punctured by a nail on the pallet. ERTS dispatched ES&H to the site to investigate the release and begin clean up operations. The contractor arrived on site and placed the proper Level B suits on to investigate the release and begin clean up operations. The contractor utilized a fork lift on site to remove the cargo on the trailer to access the released material. The damaged tote was placed into a overpacked drum prior to the environmental contractor's arrival. The contractor reported that the material had almost completely evaporated prior to their arrival. ES&H personnel neutralized the material and then cleaned up the impacted trailer floor utilizing absorbents. Three damaged boxes were also containerized for disposal along with the suits utilized by ES&H personnel. Seven drums of waste were generated from clean up activities and were transported off site for disposal. The cargo was loaded back onto the trailer for continued transportation.

On August 25, 2011, R&L Carriers contacted ERTS to manage a UN1263 Flammable Paint release located near Highway 287 and 2nd Avenue in Springfield, CO. It was reported that approximately 10 gallons of paint was released due to a loose valve on a tote. The driver reported that the valve came loose, which resulted in the released material. The driver secured the valve to stop the tote from leaking. ERTS dispatched Custom Environmental to the site to investigate the release and begin clean up operations. Custom Environmental personnel utilized a fork lift to move the totes on the trailer to access the impacted trailer floor. The contractor scaped the material from the impacted trailer floor and containerized the waste for disposal. The paint was also removed from the impacted dirt parking lot. One 55 gallon drum of waste was generated from clean up activities and was transported for disposal. No storm drains or water surfaces were impacted as a result of this release.

On August 30, 2011 at approximately 1800 hours a Linden Bulk Trailer had just started receiving a load of Ethyl Acrylate at IMTT-Bayonne when the IMTT operator noticed liquid dripping from the hose connection.  The IMTT operator immediately shut down the loading operation and placed a 5-gallon bucket under the connection to collect the dripping product.  Upon investigation it was determined that the "A-Nut" connection on the Linden trailer was not making a proper seal.  Since the leak had occurred at the outer compartment of the trailer, the IMTT operator was able to drain the remaining product without further incident.  The Linden trailer was then permitted leave IMTT.

column168: Load was booked into JB Hunts system as non-hazardous.  Load contained a non-placarded quantity of mixed limited quantity and conventional hazmat; 1801 lbs of UN1044 ltd qty, 75 lbs of UN3266 and 34 lbs of UN1013.  Shipper mistakenly handed driver flammable placards; the load did not contain any flammable materials.  Driver failed to call in to perform a hazmat briefing; he did not review his shipping papers and did not recognize the problem even when he had been provided with placards.  Because no briefing was performed, no EDI hazmat shipping paper was provided to the railcarrier, Norfolk Southern in Atlanta, GA.  When the error was brought to JBH attention, the driver and fleet manager who performed the briefing fielding the data for EDI transmission to the railroad, failed to input the data correctly - user did not select entry from a dropdown menue for "limited quantity."  This falsely showed the load as requiring dangersous placards, when in fact no placards were required, providing false information to the rail carrier.  Ad hoc transmission of EDI data also failed to transmit contract holder data for the emergency contact field; this issue has been resolved by JBH IT.
column169: JBH Compliance has recommended additional training to sales & marketing personnel to better ensure loads containing hazmat will be booked as hazmat loads, requiring the driver to perform a hazmat briefing.  Additional training and oversight has been recommended to operations personnel who perform these briefings to be sure they understand what is meant by a "limited quantity" and will be sure to enter the data correctly.  Because briefings are performed verbally, the goalkeeper in his scenario is the driver; drivers will be reminded to be sure to mention anytime a limited quantity hazardous material is present to provide the full description when fielding the data.  Increased auditing has also been recommended to better ensure accountability that the data is correctly fielded; this will be performed by comparing the EDI transmissions JBH provides with the hard copy BOLs provided by shippers.

column168: Tank car UTLX 201217 was reported leaking product from the top fitting area after UTLX 201217 was switched into an outbound BNSF train being assembled in the railyard. UTLX 201217 was then carefully moved and positioned over the railyard's containment pit. Follow-up inspection revealed product had expelled from under the thermowell assembly's closure cap. Contract responders replaced the o-ring on the thermowell stem on 8/19/2011. The o-ring removed didn't appear damaged, but had hardened which prevented a good tight seal when the thermowell closure cap was in place. Afterwards, no further product release was observed during monitoring of UTLX 201217. The internal thermometer well pipe may be compromised. All other valves and fittings were secure. Spillage on the top shell of UTLX 201217 evaporated and there was no ground impact from spillage evident.   The shipper requested a FRA OTMA to continue rail transport to destination.

A SPILL OF JP-10 (JET FUEL) OCCURRED DURING SHIPMENT, VIA RAYTHEON COMPANY VEHICLE FROM 1151 E. HERMANS RD., TUCSON, AZ TO 9000 S. RITA RD., TUCSON AZ.  THE VEHICLE WAS TRANSPORTING TWO FUELED MISSILES (UN0392, ROCKET MOTORS, LIQUID FUELED, 1.3J) IN CNU-308 NAVY-ISSUED CONTAINERS AS PART OF RAYTHEON'S NORMAL MAINTENANCE PROCESSES.  THE INCIDENT INVOLVED ONLY ONE CONTAINER.  PRIOR TO SHIPPING, THE SUBJECT MISSILE WENT THRU A MAINTENANCE PROCESS THAT INCLUDED DEFUELING THE MISSILE'S  TACTICLE PAYLOAD SECTION, REMOVING THE PAYLOAD/WARHEAD ASSEMBLY AND REPLACING THAT ASSEMBLY WITH A PAYLOAD SPACER.  THE OPERATOR PERFORMING THIS PROCESS FAILED TO RECOGNIZE THAT A TEMPORARY PAYLOAD "SPACER", CONTAINING A  PRECONFIGURED JUMPER HOSE THAT REROUTES FUEL BACK TO THE MISSILE, HAD NOT BEEN ISSUED.  INSTEAD A PRODUCTION SPACER, WITH JUMPER HOSE NOT CONFIGURED, HAD BEEN ISSUED.  AS A RESULT THE OPERATOR SELECTED THE INCORRECT WORK INSTRUCTION OPTION, WHICH OMITS THE ASSEMBLY TASK OF REROUTING A FUEL JUMPER HOSE.  WITHOUT THE CORRECT FUEL JUMPER CONFIGURATION, FUEL CAN SLOWLY TRANSFER FROM THE MISSILE INTO THE EMPTY PAYLOAD SECTION AND EVENTUALLY DRIP OUT OF THE MISSILE'S EXTERIOR WEEP HOLE INTO THE CNU-308 SHIPPING CONTAINER.  THE CNU-308 SHIPPING CONTAINER.  THE CNU-308 SHIPPING CONTAINER HAS TWO WEEP HOLES LOCARTED APPROX. 1/2" ABOVE THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER WHERE THE FUEL EVENTUALLY EXITED.  NO FUEL LEAK WAS NOTED DURING PACKAGING OR LOADING.  UPON ARRIVAL AT DESTINATION,  PRIOR TO UNLOADING, A LEAK FROM THE CNU-308 SHIPPING CONTAINER WAS OBSERVED.  RAYTHEON SECURITY AND SITE CONTRACT HAZMAT RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED AND A PERIMETER BOUNDARY WAS ESTABLISHED.  A LAYER OF AFFF FIRE-RETARDANT FOAM WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILL AND ABSORBENT SPILL CONTAINMENT TO PREVENT RUN-OFF WAS USED.  THE LEAKING UNIT WAS REMOVED FROM THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND PLACED IN A DRY CONTAINER.  CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, VEHICLE AND ASPHALT WAS THEN COMPLETED, UTILIZING A THIRD-PARTY REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR.  THE UNIT WAS LATER DRAINED OF FUEL AND THE AMOUNT MEASURED TO DETERMINE THE MAXIMUM SPILL QUANTITY OF NO MORE THAN 1/2 GALLON.
column169: Immediately halted all inbound spacer installation activity and screened all inventory for correct configuration.  Completed a Safety Review Board and added an orange stenciled 'Payload Spacer Not for Production Use' marking to clearly identify non-production spacers.  Updated work instructions/planning with photos and improved text, adding an in-line inspection to verify spacer jumper is correctly installed.  Re-torqued all fuel jumper hose connections in temporary payload spacers and eliminated the use of the production payload spacer from the planning.  Currently completing a third parry review of the improved process to assess any risks not previously noted.  Designated, with floor striping, a storage area for 'Payload Spacer Storage Only - Not For Production Use".

column168: Tank car GATX 50433 in the railyard was reported having dried product residue on its side shell that emanated from its manway closure.  No ground impact from spillage was reported. GATX 50433 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 50433 finding all manway securement bolts tool tight. Inspection of the manway gasket revealed that the gasket was torn with a 3 inch by 2 inch gasket section missing. A new manway gasket was procured and contract responders installed it on 8/26/2011. Afterwards, the responders neutralized, washed and cleaned the product residue off GATX 50433's shell. Securement and cleaning were completed by 1430 hrs. MDT, 8/26/2011. Intact seals removed were replaced by seals numbered 438606 and 438609.

August 17, 2011- CMV ANTWERPEN EXPRESS located at Norfolk International Terminals.  1320 hours- Vessel command (CMV ANTWERPEN EXPRESS) reported a leaking tank on board. Tank BLKU 2537794 loaded in Savannah on August 15 was leaking cargo onto the hatch cover. Vessel's Master notified the National Response Center and the Hapag-Lloyd vessel planner.   1415 hours - Local Hapag-Lloyd office was notified by the vessel planner. We immediately notified terminal Risk Management, Petrochem for cleanup, and appointed a marine surveyor to attend the vessel on our behalf. The shipper was notified via our Customer Service Dept. in Atlanta.  1430 hours - Norfolk Fire and Paramedic personnel arrived on sight, apparently dispatched through the N.R.C.  1600 hours- We were notified by our marine surveyor that three crewmembers were feeling sick. Shortly after some longshoremen also complained about feeling ill. All were attended to by the Norfolk Fire personnel and they were proceeding with decontamination. The three crew members were taken to the hospital for evaluation and later released and found fit for duty.  1615 HOURS - We contacted our P&I representative to attend.  1630 hours - Petrochem arrived to being containment and cleanup operations and to inspect tanks and correct the cause of the leak.  1800 hours - Vessel cargo operations stopped to resume 0800 hours on August 18. Petrochem proceeded to eliminate leak and to perform cleanup.  0800 hours August 18- Previously leaking tank and other cargo removed from vessel to effect hatch cover cleanup.

column168: On 8/17, at approx 5:45 am, while making his rounds, the Crew Leader noticed a shiny substance in the track pan and ballast on Track 5. When he approached the loader to question, the loader stated that sulfuric acid had spilled from the product cap.   1. The TM re-reviewed the SSP for transferring sulfuric acid two weeks prior to the incident occurring.  2. The importance of immediately reporting incidents was recently discussed with all terminal personnel on the heels of a previous release.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:  1. Employee did not ensure that the railcar was depressurized, per the SSP 3025-002, prior to opening the product cap.  Employee was in the habit of opening the product valve without relieving pressure from cars with a safety valve on the product line.   2. Employee was identified as learning better through repetition rather than by the SSP and was not properly monitored to ensure all necessary steps were followed to prevent incident.     CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  1. TM realigned loaders to ensure that a senior loader conducts acid transfers. A secondary loader will be assigned to ensure continuity and coverage.   2. Ensure employees are monitored and demonstrate proficiency in the task at hand prior to completing an Employee Demonstration Checklist and working unattended.   3. Certify a Spanish speaking trainer to ensure all components of the SSP are properly communicated and adhered to.

column168: On 08/30/2011 at 1130 hrs; CSX personnel in the Erwin Yard, Erwin TN reported TILX 200255, a loaded tank car of  Acetic Acid, Glacial, was leaking from the top of the rail car. column168: Tank car FURX 120552 standing on the interchange track in the railyard was reported leaking product at the bottom outlet valve (BOV) area by a Central California Traction Co. (CCT) crew. BNSF mechanical responders placed a containment receptacle under FURX 120552 and investigated the leak source. The internal BOV's mounting flange plate was the location of the product leak. One Allen head mounting bolt was found loose and it was tool tightened which stopped the leak at 1750 hrs. PDT, 8/30/2011. FURX 120552 continued to be monitored and on 8/31/2011 at approximately 0800 hrs. PDT, another product leak developed at or near the same location as the previous leak. BNSF mechanical responders again retightened  the Allen head flange securement bolts to stop this secondary leak. A verbal FRA OTMA was granted to transport FURX 120552 approximately 1 1/2 miles to its unloading location. Representatives from the FRA (FRA Inspector Flores), BNSF and CCT deemed the movement of FURX 120552 safe and it was accomplished without further incident. Captured spillage was placed into a recovery drum for shipper arrangements for either disposal or recycling.     Afterwards, information received from the CCT indicated that FURX 120552 leaked again on 9/2/2011 and DOT 5800.1 incident report numbered E-2011090149 was filed by CCT for this occurrence on their property.

column168: The train crew of a passing BNSF train on main track reported entrained rear railcar (tank car RCRX 1463) in a BNSF train parked in the siding track was emanating product vapors. Train traffic in the area was stopped until vapor emissions ebbed. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder and contract responders inspected RCRX 1463 and reported product vapor emanating in an area of 12 to 18 inches around the vapor valve. Detailed inspection of the vapor valve revealed that the vapor valve's mounting flange gasket was damaged and protruding from the valve flange connection, preventing a good seal. The vapor valve's flange bolts were tool tight. A replacement gasket was installed and the vapor valve resecured. The vapor valve flange area was checked for any leakage and none observed. Seals BP 578 and BP 579 were applied. A neutralizing solution was sprayed onto all non-evaporated tank shell spillage.  On 8/26/2011, a mobile tank car repair crew successfully completed a leakproffness test on RCRX 1463.   RCRX 1463's side specification stencil indicated that it was last qualified in the year 2007 and next due in 2017.

column168: THE BOX WAS PICKED UP FROM THE DRIVER.

SWA'S INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT, AT THE TIME THE REPAIR KIT WAS INDUCTED INTO SWA'S MATERIAL INVENTORY, IT WAS NOT FLAGGED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (HAZMAT) IN THE SYSTEM.  THE LACK OF SUCH FLAG RESULTED IN A FAILURE TO PRINT THE WORD HAZMAT ON THE SA-M 858 LABEL WHICH WAS ATTACHED TO THE REPAIR KIT AT THE TIME OF INDUCTION INTO THE SYSTEM.  THE ABSENCE OF THE WORD HAZMAT ON THE SA-M 858 LABEL WAS A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR TO THE OCCURRENCE OF THE EVENT.                                                                         SWA'S INVESTIGATION ALSO DETERMINED THAT AN ADDITIONAL CONTRIBUTING FACTOR TO THIS EVENT WAS THE FAILURE OF A SWA MATERIAL SPECIALIST TO PROCESS THE PICK-TICKET IN ACCORDANCE WITH A DEPARTMENTAL POLICY, WHICH PROVIDES THAT IT IS "... THE LEAD STOCK CLERK'S RESPONSIBILITY TO SEGREGATE ALL HAZMAT TICKETS FROM ALL OTHER TICKETS, AND ASSIGN THE HAZMAT TICKETS TO AN INDIVIDUAL STOCK CLERK FOR PROCESSING."                                    ON 08/07/2011, A MATERIAL SPECIALIST LOCATED IN DAL OPENED THE SHIPMENT AND DISCOVERED THE REPAIR KIT.  THE LEADER ON DUTY  WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND THE REPAIR KIT WAS QUANRANTINED.  AN INVESTIGATION WAS IMMEDIATELY CONDUCTED THAT VERIFIED THE ITEM WAS HAZMAT AND THAT IT SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN SHIPPED ON A SWA AIRCRAFT.
column169: THE PHX MATERIAL SPECIALIST INVOLVED IN THIS EVENT WAS VERBALLY COUNSELED ON 08/09/2011.  THE COUNSELING REITERATED THE  IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING SWA HAZMAT HANDLING PROCEDURES AND POLICIES AND THE SEVERITY OF THIS TYPE OF FAILURE.  THE PHX MATERIAL SPECIALIST WAS ISSUED A LETTER OF INSTRUCTION ON 08/23/2011.  MATERIAL SPECIALIST LETTER OF INSTRUCTION THE PHX MATERIALS SPECIALIST HAS ALSO COMPLETED A HUMAN ERROR MANAGEMENT COURSE ON 08/23/2011.                                                                 A MATERIAL STORES INSTRUCTIONAL LEADER TURNED ON THE HAZMAT FLAG WITHIN WIZARD TO SHOW THAT THE REPAIR KIT, STOCK ITEM # (SI) 1981332 IS IDENTIFIED AS "HAZMAT."  WIZARD SCREEN SHOT INDICATING SI# 1981332 AS HAZMAT.                                                                     IMMEDIATELY, THE REPAIR KIT STORAGE LOCATION LOCATED IN THE STOCKROOM WAS PROPERLY IDENTIFIED AS A HAZMAT STORAGE AREA.  REPAIR KIT STORAGE AREA PHOTO PHX.  THE REMAINING SWA MAINTENANCE BASES AND LINE STATIONS WILL HAVE THE REPAIR KIT STORAGE AREAS INDENTIFIED NO LATER THAN 09/03/2011.                       ALL SWA MATERIAL SPECIALISTS HAVE BEEN BRIEFED BY MATERIAL LEADERSHIP ON SWA'S HAZMAT HANDLING PROCEDURES, WITH AN EMPHASIS ON THE DEPARTMENTAL POLICY PERTAINING TO PROCESSING PICK-TICKETS AND SEGREGATION OF HAZMAT ITEMS FROM NON-HAZMAT ITEMS.                                                                                       SWA IS IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTING A SECONDARY VALIDATION AUTHORIZATION FOR COMAT, AOG AND HAZMAT SHIPMENTS PRIOR TO  RELEASE.  THIS PROCESS INVOLVES USING A CHECKLIST FOR HAZMAT ITEMS, AND TWO MATERIAL SPECIALISTS VALIDATING THE PICK-TICKETS AND AIR BILLS PRIOR TO FINAL PACKAGING AND RELEASE OF THE PACKAGES.  THIS PROCESS WILL BE IMPLEMENTED NO LATER THAN 09/05/2011.

column168: BNSF was notified by CHEMTREC that a citizen reported tank car AMCX 25813 (standing on an interchange track) appeared to be leaking product. Nearby BNSF personnel confirmed that AMCX 25813 was emanating a strong product odor. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder and contract responders inspected AMCX 25813. Responders reported that AMCX 25813's liquid valve had a small product leak at its threaded connection. Product spillage on AMCX 25813's side shell was evaporating and no product spillage impacted the ground. Detailed inspection of the liquid valve revealed that it was loose on its threaded connection, the valve itself was partially open, its closure plug was only hand tight and the valve stem was damaged (seized in an open position).  Inspection of the vapor valve revealed that it was partially open with its closure plug only hand tight and the valve stem also appeared damaged and inoperable. The responders tightened the liquid valve on its threaded connection and tool tightened the loose closure plugs by 2158 hrs. CDT, 8/24/2011. After this securement was completed, no further product leaks or odor was evident. The shipper was notified of the liquid and vapor valve deficiencies and AMCX 25813 was returned to the shipper's nearby loading location for corrective repairs.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF yard crew noticed a strong chemical odor near tank car AMCX 25801 in the railyard and then observed AMCX 25801 leaking product down its side shell. AMCX 25801 was cordoned-off in the railyard. Contract responders inspected AMCX 25801 finding the leak source at the threaded liquid valve connection. The liquid valve was in its closed position, but was very loose on its threaded connection and its closure plug was not applied (but present lying within the valve hosing area). The vapor valve was found in its full open position, but its closure plug was tool tight and holding back vapor pressure. The responders closed the vapor valve.  The liquid valve and its closure plug were properly tool tightened on their threaded connections after additional Teflon tape applied to the threaded areas. Non-evaporated spillage on the side shell of AMCX 25801 was wiped. Micro-Blaze microbial treatment was applied atop spillage that impacted ballast as a bioremediation agent and odor reducer. Response concluded by 1841 hrs. CDT, 8/26/2011.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: LOADING AT KOCH NITROGEN IN ENID OKLAHOMA.  PRIOR TO LOADING, CARGO TANK PRESSURES WERE RUNNING HIGHER DUE TO AIR TEMPERATURES OF 100 PLUS DEGREES.  DRIVER AND LOADER WERE MONITORING TANK PRESSURE OF CARGO TANK DURING LOADING.  JUST WHEN THE TANK WAS LOADED AND THE PUMP SHUT OFF POSSIBLY CAUSING A SURGE IN PRESSURE, ONE OF THE RELIEF VALUES RELEASED PRESSURE FOR 3 SECONDS. Our vehicle arrived at consignee for delivery of product. Driver of vehicle contacted consignee personnel for presentation of shipping papers and instructions for delivery. Consignee verfied delivery amount and capacity in storage tank, then proceed to instruct driver to transfer product into storage tank. Consignee signed our authorization to unload and driver proceeded to transfer product to storage tank by pressurizing cargo tank with compressed air. Near the end of transfer process diver noticed product on ground around the storage tank. It was apparent that storage tank could not hold the entire amount and excess leaked from back of storage tank through vent and onto the ground. Driver notified consignee and carrier. Consignee personnel responded to spill and driver was released.
column169: Storage tank design allowed an overflow to occur beyound the driver's field of vision. Due to this design, consignee should have been in attendance monitoring the storage tank liquid level. Storage tank design and delivery site inspections are helpful in preventing this type of incident.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed fresh product on the side shell of entrained tank car NATX 37035 and also product spray on an adjacent tank car entrained behind NATX 37035. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected NATX 37035 that resulted in an initial determination that NATX 37035 may be overfilled, as all valves and fittings appeared secure. Both NATX 37035 and the other rail car were carefully isolated in the railyard. A follow-up detailed inspection by a response contractor determined that the liquid valve on NATX 37035 was loose on its threaded connection and this was the source of the product leak.  The liquid valve's operating handle interfered with the full closure of the valve housing cover when the valve was fully tightened on its threaded connection; therefore the liquid valve was not tool tightened to accommodate the housing cover's closure. The responders tool tightened the liquid valve on its threaded connection and removed the liquid valve's operating handle. The valve handle was secured within the valve housing area. The contract responders steam cleaned both rail cars after plastic sheeting was laid under the rail cars to capture rinsed liquids and protect the ground.  NATX 37035's intact valve housing cover seal numbered 0000913 was replaced by seal BNSF 06157428.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

tank cars loaded with crude oil were randomly inspected in Riker, PA yard by DOT on a train that was scheduled to depart for Bradford, PA.  A small amout of liquid was noticed on the side of 2 cars by the inspector.  Local rr management was notified and assessed the situation.  Both cars were switched out at the yard and buckets were placed under the side ladders if any material came off the side of the cars so it would not go on ground.  A local haz mat repair company was summonned and it was found that both cars had cut manway gaskets probably caused by overtigening of manway bolts.  Both gaskets replaced and manway bolts tightened to proper tightness.
column169: 1)Better training for loaders of the crude oil at point of origination.    2) More random inspection of these cars to determine if there is a systematical issue with overthghtened manway bolts.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at 704 Dunn Way a leak was discovered coming from the trailer.  The trailer was isolated and NRC Environmental Services, Inc. of Long Beach, CA was dispatched to inspect the trailer and complete site cleanup.  NRC Environmental Services, Inc. inspected the leaking trailer and discovered one (1) leaking 55-gallon drum.  The leak was the result of a puncture on the bottom of the drum.  Approximately 20 gallons of free product were released.  NRC Environmental Services, Inc. deployed sodium carbonate on the impacted area of the road.  The leaking drum was placed into an over-pack drum for disposal.  The freight from the leaking trailer was trans-loaded into a new trailer.  NRC Environmental Services, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Roadrunner Transportation Services, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Please note this incident is still being thoroughly investigated. Driver stopped for fuel and noticed the leaking drum as he was checking his cargo. Driver called Veolia dispatch for assistance, a field service crew was mobilizied to assist. The leaking drum was identified by the driver. It was discovered that the drum had a vertical score on the side of the drum that started about 2 to 3 inches from the top of the drum and ran down to about 6 inches below the upper rib. The score got progessively deeper along the side of the drum until it cut through the first rib. Absorbent material was used to absorb the leaking material in the trailer and on the ground below the trailer. Clean-up materials (absorbent) was collected and containerized for disposal. The damaged drum was placed into an 95 gallon salvage drum.
column169: It was not determined if the drum was damaged during transportation or prior. In the future, verify the condition of all drums prior to loading. Do not load any drums that are damaged. Make sure that all packages are secure and that they are no projections that could damage cargo.

ON 08/22/2011, A LEAD MATERIAL SPECIALIST BASED AT DALLAS LOVE FIELD AIRPORT, DALLAS, TX (DAL) WAS PULLING PICK-TICKETS TO BE PROCESSED, IN ADDITION TO PULLING PARTS AND PLACING THEM ON A CART TO BE ISSUED.  THE LEAD MATERIAL SPECIALIST PULLED A VALVE  DIVERTER, FIRE PROTECTION MPN 52000859-1, S/N 00148, SWA STOCK ITEM # (SI) 0260039 FROM AN AREA THAT WAS CLEARLY MARKED WITH CANDY-STRIPE TAPE, INDICATING THAT THE AREA CONTAINED HAZMAT PARTS.  AFTER THE PART WAS PULLED, A MATERIAL SPECIALIST RAISED  CONCERNS TO THE LEAD MATERIAL SPECIALIST THAT THE PART MAY BE HAZMAT.  THE LEAD MATERIAL SPECIALIST RESPONDED THAT THE PART WAS A FUEL COMPONENT THAT CAME BACK FROM THE VENDOR AND WAS OK TO SHIP.  FOLLOWING THE LEAD MATERIALS SPECIALIST'S RESPONSE, THE MATERIAL SPECIALIST PLACED THE VALVE DIVERTER ON A CART INDICATING THAT THE PART WAS READY FOR PACKAGING AND SHIPMENT TO SKY HARBOR INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT, PHOENIX, AZ (PHX).  THE PART WAS ULTIMATELY SHIPPED UNDECLARED ON A SWA FLIGHT FROM DAL TO PHX.
column169: The two DAL Material Specialists involved in this event were verbally counseled on 08/30/2011.  The counseling reiterated the importance of following SWA HAZMAT handling procedures and policies and the severity of this type of failure.  The DAL Lead and Material Specialist were given copies of the departmental HAZMAT Handling Procedures and were reviewed in length with Stores Leadership to ensure the procedures were thoroughly understood.  The DAL Lead and Material Specialist were issued Letters of Instruction on 08/30/2011 that outlined the details of each individual's involvement in this HAZMAT event.  Letter of Instruction (2 each).  Existing HAZMAT pick-ticket and order fulfillment policies and procedures were reinforced through crew briefings and one-on-ones.  Attendance was taken at these events to ensure all DAL stores employees received the informational briefings in a timely manner.  SWA is immediately implementing a secondary validation authorization for Comat, AOG and HAZMAT shipments prior to release.  This process involves using a checklist for HAZMAT items, and two Material Specialists validating the pick-tickets and air bills prior to final packaging and release of all packages. This process is intended to serve as an additional control to prevent future inadvertent shipments of undeclared items and has been implemented at all SWA stores locations as of 09/05/2011.  SWA is establishing segregated storage and processing areas for HAZMAT items at SWA Maintenance Bases and Line Maintenance Stations, specifically including caged areas at SWA Maintenance Bases, with an anticipated completion by end of

column168: An eastbound train hauling 62 loads of coal was pulling into track #10 in Clearfield Yard. A rail broke under movement  of the train and began derailing cars 46 through 48. Car #47 struck the FURX 844006 (Ammonium Nitrate) standing on track #9, puncturing the B end of the standing car. The standing car was then shoved east against the #46 car, puncturing the left side near the B end. Both punctures were near the top of the car and approximately 2 feet in length. Approximately 3,900 LBS of product was released from the car. The location of spilled product was isolated and covered with plastic and location was assessed to ensure runoff to any local water source would not occur. Non essential employees were kept clear or the area. The clean­ up of the spilled product consisted of 5 employees wearing goggles, dust respirators, long sleeve shirts, and gloves. The spilled product was placed in 2 clean plastic totes (275 gal), using clean shovels, and shop vac. Totes were then covered loosely, and relocated to a safe and secure area away from any fuel source. Placards were placed on all 4 sides of totes to identify the product.
column169: ALTHOUGH A RAIL BROKE UNDER MOVEMENT OF THE TRAIN, WE WILL CONTINUE TO REMAIN VIGILANT FOR TRACK DEFECTS, PAYING PARTICULAR ATTENTION TO YARD/SECONDARY TRACKS.  THIS INCIDENT WILL BE USED AS A TRAINING TOOL TO EDUCATE PRESENT AND FUTURE EMPLOYEES ON SAFE WORK PRACTICES AND HAZMAT PROCEDURES.

column168: CN transportation department employee noted vapors coming from the top of tank car GATX 4670 (L/ HYDROCHLORIC ACID) during normal operations at CN's LaPlace Yard, LA. All appropriate departments notified, car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the rupture disk housing flange bolts were less than tool tight allowing vapors to escape.  Housing properly secured and the leak stopped. Tank car released for movement to destination.

CN transportation department employee noted vapors coming from the top of tank car GATX 57602 (L / Hydrochloric Acid) during switching operations at the CN New Yard, Presidents Island, Memphis, TN. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting that the rupture disk had failed allowing product to escape. Rupture disk assembly was equipped with surge protection and secured with shipper's seal. New disk installed and car deconned of product. Tank car released for movement to destination.

column168: RESPONDED TO THE LOAD LINES.  PKG LEAKING POWDER.  FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE FOR PROCESSING USED, NON-FLAMMABLE GAS RESPONSE SHEET (NON-FLAMMABLE GAS DIAMOND LABEL).  WORE REQUIRED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  PLACED PKG IN DMP BAG FOLLOWING UPS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.
column169: PIN CAME OUT OF EXTINGUISHER DURING TRANSIT.

column168: RESPONDED TO SPILL IN FULL PPE.  SAW IT AS A HAZMAT LEAKER.  TESTED WITH PH TAPE.  FOUND ITEM TO BE IN SAFE RANGE, THEN BAGGED CONTENTS AND PUT IN SPILL TRAY AND RETURNED TO THE DMP TO FURTHER PROCESS THE PACKAGE.
column169: BAG BOTTLE PACK BETTER FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: A HAZMAT PACKAGE APPROX. 2FT DROPPED ONTO THE IRREG SLIDE & IT STARTED LEAKING.  SUPERVISOR, NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY WHEN RESPONDER ARRIVED UTILIZED DECISION TREE / RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  I ALTERED PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHEILD INNER LINERS.  CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY.  USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID ON THE CHUTE & FLOOR TO A PH LEVEL BETWEEN 6 - 9. SOLIDIFIED THE LIQUID ON THE CHUTE & FLOOR WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT.  SWEPT UPALL THE SODIUM BICARB/ABSORBANT MIXTURE & PUT IT IN THE LINED SPILL TRAY WITH THE LEAKING PACKAGE.  THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TOTHE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. THEN OPENED THE BOX, FOUND THAT 1 OF THE 4 BOTTLES WAS CRUSHED & HAD CRACKED.  THE OTHER 3 BOTTLES WERE INTACT, BUT CONTAMINATED BY THE PRODUCT.
CALLED FOR HAZMAT LEAKER TO PD 4.  BOX FELL OFF BELT CAUSING BOTTLE TO BREAK.  WORE PPE, FOLLOWED DECESION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET.
THE PACKAGE WAS RESPONDED TO USING THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  THEN PROCESSED ACCORDING TO DMP PROCEDURES.

UNLOADER SAW A DISCOLORED FLAMMABLE LIQUID MARKED PARCEL, NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR, RESPONDER PERFORMED PPE, USED DECISION TREE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  CONTAINED ALL MATERIALS, REMOVED THEM TO DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

Contractor operators were preparing to unload crude oil from a railcar. The bottom unload valve on the railcar was not fully seated closed resulting in the discharge of approximately 85 BBL of Crude oil in the ground. The cause of the release was a defective valve that was not fully closed.
column169: Ensure shippers pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it related to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings. In addition, NuStar has arranged with the shipper to no deliver rail cars with the internal bottom loading valves.

column42: ETHYL METHYL KETONE OR METHYL ETHYL KETONE
column168: CN engineering department employee reported a strong odor coming from tank car, XOMX 110011 (R/ Last Contained: Methyl Ethyl Ketone) during a roll by inspection of train M39931-22. All appropriate departments notified, train stopped and tank car isolated in track. CN response team responded, noting two manway cover swing bolts hanging down and three bolts less than tool tight, allowing vapors to be released. Shipper's seal intact. Bolts tightened securing the manway, odor dissipated, tank car and train released for movement.

CN mechanical department employee noted a small amount product dripping from the bottom outlet cap of tank car TAEX 336(L / Flammable Liquid, N.O.S. - Heavy Fuel Oil) during an inspection at the CN Champaign Yard, Urbana, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the bottom outlet valve handle in the closed position, shipper's seal intact and product dripping from the outlet cap. Further inspection found the outlet cap less than tool tight allowing product to escape. Cap properly secured, tank car released for movement.

NARRATIVE: On 8/30, at about 10:10 am on Track 3, an Ethanol transfer was being conducted. Loader input incorrect amount to be loaded into trailer into the meter, causing 12 gallons of Ethanol to be released.    AWARENESS ITEMS:   1. This release occurred on the second half of a split load.   2. The locks were not engaged on the scully.  3. Carrier’s certificate shows that they reduce compartments by 60 gallons as an additional safeguard, but this was not the case in this incident.  4. The scully was in the auto position; this was verified by the Terminal Manager and Director of Operations.   5. No red light was observed to indicate that there wasn’t a ground.  6. Ensure there are spill pans in place under the overflow tubes; depending on the configuration of the trailer they can be located in different places.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:   1. Total amount to be transferred was 2050 gallons.  The 1st part of split was 598 gallons, leaving 1452 gallons to be transferred. The loaders were switched mid load and the second loader, by instinct, input total load amount versus the split amount.      CONTRIBUTING FACTORS:  1. A separate loader filled compartments 1-4 and part of 5. He was pulled off the load and another loader was used to complete the remainder of 5.   2. A faulty pump ground wire was confirmed by outside electrician. It is believed that this may have contributed to scully not operating properly.   3. Carrier’s certificate shows that they reduce compartments by 60 gallons as an additional safeguard, but this was not the case in this incident. The carriers probe was set to the highest level so they could Max out his compartment.     CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:   1. Loaders should never be changed mid load. This increases the potential for error to occur due to improper or misunderstood Instructions.   2. Raise awareness to ensure correct numbers of gallons are entered into meter, per SSP 3025-012.  3. Electricians called to investigate faulty ground.  Ground wire has since been repaired.   4. SSP needs to be updated to reflect that all safety devices must be locked and keys controlled by management.   5. Update 1642B to reflect scully must be locked at all times.

The Linde driver arrived at Intel and backed the truck to the dock and unloaded to full cylinders.  The driver then loaded two empty (residual) onto the vehicle.  At this time he was distracted by a request from an Intel employee to pickup additional cylinders at another location within the Intel facility.  The driver proceeded to the truck and began to move when one of the two cylinders loaded fell from the rear of the vehicle as a reesult of the driver not strapping the cylinders in place.  The driver had been distracted from his normal routine.  The cylinder fell onto the valve protection cap, bending the base (neckring) to which the cap attaches.  The cap made contact with the valve, bending the valve at the point which it enters the cylinder body.  A barely audible release of the residual nitrogen occured.  The leak was at the piont that the cylinder valve enters the cylinder body.  The release of nitrogen at the slow rate lasted less than one hour.  As Nitrogen is an inert gas, no mitigation efforts were taken to stop the minor release.
column169: The driver was immediately disqualified as a driver and was suspended pending investigation.  The driver subsequently resigned.    The cylinder involved in the incident was quarrantined and will be requalified and inspected prior to returning to use.  The damaged valve will be replaced as well as the neck ring.    Additional trainng and information will be provided to all drivers as a result of this incident, focusing on staying on routine and not allowing distractions to intervene with safety activities.  Drivers are adequately trained to properly secure cylinders and to not move vehicles without securing the lifgate in the fully up polsition.  In this case, loss of focus has been determined to be the root cause.

column169: USE DUNNAGE, DECK BARS AND AIR BAGS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE FOR SAFE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFETY-CHECKED TO ENSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.
