column168: 1)  Sequence of Events for Contaminated Trailer# 3830067     •  Trailer 3830067 was used to transport 2 sealand containers from a customer and arrived on site at Studsvik Processing Facility Memphis (SPFM) on 8/18/2011.  •  The 2 sealand containers were surveyed and received.  •  A "return to service" survey was performed on trailer# 3830067 as required by 49 CFR 173.443. The survey results were <.5 mrem/hr gamma on contact,< 2200 dpm/100cm2  beta-gamma smearable contamination, and < 220 dpm/100cm2  alpha smearable contamination.  .  On 8/19/2011intermodal waste containers # IM-026 and IM-049 were loaded on trailer# 3830067 and shipped to Clive, Utah for disposal. The shipment number was 0893-04-0395  .  The shipment was received by EnergySolutions (ES) on 8/22/2011 or  8/23/2011.  •  A "return to service" survey on trailer#  3830067 was performed and in addition to the requirements of 49 CFR 173.443 a direct frisk for beta­ gamma contamination was performed.  •  A 2"x2" section of the wood on the trailer was found to be reading 77,000 dpm per direct frisk.  •  4 cloth disk smears were taken on the identified 2"x2" section of the trailer and the results were < 66 dpm/100 cm2 smearable beta-gamma contamination and < 9 dpm/100 cm2 smearable alpha contamination.  •  Since the cloth disk smears did not remove the contamination, oily Masslinn cloth was used to wipe the identified 2"x2" section. The Masslinn removed the contamination from the identified 2"x2" section and the  reported result was 55,000 dpm/100cm2.
column169: 2) SPFM Corrective Action to Prevent a Recurrence of the Incident  .  SPFM is purchasing a Ludlum Model 239-1F Floor Monitor which will be used to survey all flatbed trailers for beta-gamma contamination destined for Clive, Utah.  •  Since the floor monitor will take 6 weeks for delivery, all trailers will be surveyed by direct frisk for beta-gamma contamination prior to loading waste containers.

column168: WHILE OFF-LOADING INTO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST) AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, A PASSENGER VEHICLE IMPACTED THE OFF-LOADING HOSE ASSEMBLY CAUSING A DETACHMENT FROM THE TANK CAR VALVE. THE SHIPPER/CARRIER PERSONNEL CONDUCTING THE OFF-LOADING IMMEDIATELY SHUT-OFF THE FLOW OF DIESEL FUEL AT THE VALVE. APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ASPHALT AS A RESULT OF THE VEHICULAR IMPACT. NO DAMAGE TO THE TANK CAR OR VALVE RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.  THE FLORENCE VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT (VFD) WAS CONTACTED BY A WITNESS AT THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL THE VFD APPLIED - 900 GALLONS OF WATER AND SOAP SOLUTION TO THE SPILL AREA WITH A HIGH PRESSURE SYSTEM WHICH REMOVED THE DIESEL FUEL FROM THE ASPHALT. THE RINSATE FROM THE VFD'S ACTIVITIES ENTERED THE NEARBY STORM WATER SYSTEM. WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS (WCEC) ARRIVED ONSITE AT - 12:00 AND BEGAN ASSESSMENT AND MITIGATION ACTIONS RELATED TO THE RINSATE FLOWPATH AND ENTRY INTO THE STORM WATER SYSTEM. ABSORBENT PAD AND BOOMS WERE USED TO RECOVER ALL AVAILABLE FREE-PHASE DIESEL FUEL PRESENT IN THE ACCESSIBLE AREAS OF THE STORM DRAIN. APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF DIESEL IMPACTED WATER WAS PUMPED AND TREATED FOR DISPOSAL. FURTHER ASSESSMENT AND REMEDIATION IS UNDER CONSIDERATION BY THE MONTANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.

column168: The 3axle tank truck with 2axle pull trailer was westbound on Hwy128 through curves and over hills. Truck was headed down hill, navigated a left hand curve, at the exit of that curve, the downhill grade increases and then goes into a sharper right hand turn. The firefighters and CHP Officers on scene later informed me that his right hand curve is banked incorrectly, it banks to the left, and they have had several incidents there.  More than likely the driver was traveling too fast for conditions and his last minute attempts to brake as the road grade became steaper may have caused the liquid surge to increase or amplify just prior to entering the right hand curve. As the surge was coming from the right rear headed forward towards the left front, I believe this aided in a whip effect as the truck headed around the right hand curve. I believe this effect was also amplified by the efficency of the ABS brakes in conjunction with the air ride suspension, which causes the trailer to "sit down" or squat, and then when the brakes are released, you get an upward spring like motion. So as the truck rounded the entrance of the right hand curve, the forward left liquid surge, the upward spring motion of the brakes releasing the stored energy in the suspension and combined with the whip of the truck rounding the right hand curve, caused the trailer to roll to the left, at the exact moment that a car was passing the truck in the opposite direction. The trailer rolled on top of and then across the car, killing the occupant instantly. The trailer, now sliding on it's upper left side and vapor rails, continued to swing and slide to the left until it struck the dirt hillside and then rebounded back onto the roadway and behind the truck, which was still decelerating but never left it's lane. During the rollover, the safety/keeper bolt, which holds the pintle eye retainer nut in place, broke loose and fell onto the roadway as the trailer rolled over it.  The keeper bolt punctured and remained lodged in the shell of the tank, which was the spill sources. There were three other spill sources 1-2 inches long by 1/4-1/2 inches wide as a result of the shell impacting and sliding along the asphalt. The impact also dislodged all of the internal bulkheads, which essencially turned the three compartment trailer into a one compartment, and since there was still a slight downhill grade, the product drained from the back to the front and out of the four spill sources in the shell. Once the driver was able to stop the truck and set the brakes, and before being pulled away by bystandards, he thought to pull the emergency shutoff for the air supply to the truck's product delivery system. The driver did the same for the trailer but as this was not one of the sources, it did not aid in any containment. Due to the amount of product flowing, the driver did not attempt to put out diapers or booms as he would not have been able to contain the volume flowing. I arrived on scene just afte
column169: We have already made changes to our training program as a result of this incident. Unfortunately we've found that the most effective tool is providing our drivers with the details of this incident and the knowledge that it was one of their own. Just because someone has over 10 years with the company and over 20 years driving experience doesn't mean that they can be complacent in thier driving habits. We have also started installing roll-over protection systems that are integrated with the ABS systems.

column168: UNIT #1 WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND IN THE 900 BLOCK OF WEST HWY 114 IN THE LEFT LANE WITH UNIT #2 IN TOW. UNIT #3 WAS STATIONARY IN THE 1100 BLOCK OF LITSEY ROAD IN THE RIGHT LANE FACING NORTHBOUND AT THE SIGNAL LIGHT. UNIT #1 RAN THE RED LIGHT AT THE INTERSECTION OF SH 114 AND LITSEY ROAD TRAVELING EASTBOUND. UNIT #3 WAS PROCEEDING NORTHBOUND THROUGH THE INTERSECTION ON A GREEN LIGHT AND WAS STRUCK BY UNIT #2. AFTER THE COLLISION, UNIT #1 TRAVELED TO THE 700 BLOCK OF WEST SH 114 AND STOPPED ON THE LEFT SHOULDER PARTIALLY IN THE LEFT LANE. AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION, UNIT #2 CAUGHT ON FIRE AND COMPLETELY DESTROYED UNIT #2 AND UNIT #1. DUE TO THE EXTENSIVE DAMAGE CAUSED BY THE FIRE I WAS UNABLE TO DETERMINE THE EXACT POINT OF CONTACT ON UNIT #2. IT APPEARED FROM THE DAMAGE TO UNIT #3 THAT THE RIGHT REAR TIRES OF UNIT #2 STRUCK THE LEFT FRONT QUARTER PANEL OF UNIT #3 AND ROLLED OVER THE HOOD AND ENGINE COMPARTMENT OF UNIT #3.  THERE WAS AN UNINVOLVED MOTORIST WHO WAS STOPPED IN THE LEFT LANE NEXT TO UNIT #3 WHO WITNESSED THE ACCIDENT. THE NORTHBOUND TRAFFIC ON LITSEY ROAD. THE WITNESS ADVISED THAT SHE STARTED TO PROCEED THROUGH THE INTERSECTION BUT OBSERVED UNIT #1 APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED AND IT APPEARED THAT UNIT #1 WAS NOT GOING TO STOP. THE WITNESS STATED THAT SHE STOPPED AND OBSERVED UNIT #3 PROCEED NORTHBOUND THROUGH THE INTERSECTION ON A GREEN LIGHT. THE WITNESS OBSERVED UNIT #1 RUN THE RED LIGHT AND WATCHED AS UNIT #2 AND UNIT #3 COLLIDED.  DRIVER OF UNIT #1 ADVISED THAT AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF SH 114 EASTBOUND AND LITSEY ROAD HE OBSERVED THAT HIS SIGNAL LIGHT WAS YELLOW. DRIVER OF UNIT #1 PROCEEDED THROUGH THE INTERSECTION AND OBSERVED BOTH UNIT #3 AND THE UNINVOLVED MOTORIST OUT OF HIS PASSENGER SIDE WINDOW. DRIVER OF UNIT #1 STATED THAT HE OBSERVED BOTH VEHICLES START TO MOVE AS HE WAS CLEARING THE INTERSECTION. DRIVER OF UNIT #1 STATED THAT AS HE WAS CLEARING THE INTERSECTION HE NOTICED THAT THE UNINVOLVED MOTORIST STOPPED BUT UNIT #3 KEPT ADVANCING TOWARD HIM. DRIVER OF UNIT #1 THEN LOOKED INTO HIS PASSENGER SIDE REAR VIEW MIRROR AND WATCHED AS UNIT #3 AND UNIT #2 STRUCK. DRIVER OF UNIT #1 WAS UNSURE IF UNIT #3 STRUCK UNIT #2 OR IF UNIT #3 STOPPED AND WAS THEN STRUCK BY UNIT #2.  DRIVER OF UNIT #3 ADVISED THAT HIS LIGHT HAD CHANGED TO GREEN AND HE PROCEEDED NORTHBOUND ON LITSEY ROAD THROUGH THE INTERSECTION. DRIVER OF UNIT #3 ADVISED THAT HE WAS UNABLE TO SEE UNIT #1 APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION DUE TO A VEHICLE IN THE LEFT LANE BLOCKING HIS VIEW. DRIVER OF UNIT #3 ADVISED THAT AS HE TRAVELED TRHOUGH THE INTERSECTION HE WAS STRUCK. DRIVER OF UNIT #3 ADVISED THAT HE DOES NOT KNOW IF HE WAS STRUCK BY UNIT #1 OR UNIT #2.

column168: THE DRIVER FOR DILLON TRANSPORT ENTERED INTO THE MOSAIC FACILITY ON AUGUST 8, 2011 TO LOAD SULFURIC ACID. THE DRIVER STAGE THE CARGO TANK ON THE EAST SIDE LOADING RACK AND SECURED THE UNIT FOR LOADING. THE DRIVER ENTERED THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO BE LOADED AND ACTIVATED THE LOADING PROCESS FOR THE WEST SIDE LOAD-OUT. THE CARGO TANK WAS NOT STAGED AT THE WEST SIDE LOAD-OUT. BY ENTERING THE AMOUNT INTO THE WRONG CONTROLLER CAUSED THE LOADING ARM TO ACTIVATE ONCE THE DRIVER DEPRESSED THE FOOT PEDAL DISCHARGING PRODUCT THROUGH THE LOADING ARM INTO THE PLANT CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE LOAD-OUT AREA. THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON AN CONCRETE SURFACE WITHIN THE PLANTS CONTAINMENT AREA. THERE WAS NO FAILURE TO THE CARGO TANK AS NO PRODUCT ENTERED THE VESSEL DUE TO THE DRIVER'S FAILURE TO ACTIVATE THE CORRECT LOADING ARM. THE TIME-LINE AROUND THE RELEASE WOULD BE ESTIMATED AROUND 10 TO 15 SECONDS. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE AREA OR ANY OF THE EQUIPMENT.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED BASED ON THE INCIDENT. DILLION TRANSPORT AND MOSAIC MEET TO DISCUSS ACTIONS TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE. A LIMIT SWITCH WAS INSTALLED ON THE LOADING LINE TO PREVENT THE CONTROLLER FROM BEING ACTIVATED UNLESS THE LOADING LINE IS AT A HORIZONTAL POSITION. ORANGE WITH BLACK LETTERS WERE INSTALLED OVER EACH CONTROLLER NOTING EAST AND WEST LOAD-OUT. A STEEL RAILING WAS ALSO INSTALLED DIVIDING THE EAST AND WEST LOAD-OUT STATIONS AT THE CONTROLLERS THAT IDENTIFIES THE LOAD-OUTS INDEPENDENT FROM ONE ANOTHER.

column168: ADM contracted Safety Kleen to empty and clean our chemical tanks so we could remove them. Safety Kleen sub contracted the job to Clean Ventures Environmental who sub contracted the trucking of the hydrogen peroxide to Freehold Cartage (FCI). Clean Ventures arrived Monday, August 22, 2011 at 7:00am with 4 people to begin the process of emptying the hydrogen peroxide tanks. Freehold Cartage also arrived on site at 7:00 am. When the Clean Venture employee opened the manway on top of the outside hydrogen peroxide tank, the liquid appeared stable inside and no fumes or vapors were present that escaped out of the tank. The tanker had 12-15 inches of vacuum before the valve leading to the hose in the tank was opened. The hose was supplied by FCI and was placed through the top manway of the outside tank and held in place by a Clean Venture employee. Immediately the pressure in the tanker went from vacuum to approximately 35 psi and there was white colored gas escaping from all 3 manways and around the pump. The liquid in the hose blew back into the outside tank and created so much pressure the Clean Venture employee had a hard time restraining the hose. The operation was stopped while the FCI driver called his dispatcher. The FCI driver told the Clean Venture supervisor the products should be compatible and was told to attempt the operation again. Approximately 8:30am, they pulled vacuum on the tanker and opened the valve to the hose and the reaction was the same. The tanker went immediately to a pressure state, there was visible white gas escaping from the tanker and the hose back to the tank pressured up. The Clean Venture supervisor stopped the job and instructed the FCI driver to wash out the tanker. The FCI driver left site at 8:57 am to go to Pedricktown Tank Wash but left the hoses that had been in use on site.   The FCI tanker returned to site at 10:51am. When the Clean Venture employee returned to the manway on top of the outside hydrogen peroxide tank, the liquid once again appeared stable inside and no fumes or vapors were present that escaped out of the tank. They resumed operations at 11:09am using the same hoses that were used earlier in the day. They were finished pumping out the hydrogen peroxide within 30 minutes and had no issues with gas escaping from the tanker or the tanker pressuring up. The outside tank was triple rinsed using a pressure washer supplied by Clean Venture that had been filled from the city water tap at the Glassboro plant earlier that morning. The pH of the rinse water was checked and the water was also loaded into the tanker.    Approximately 12:30pm, they moved inside to empty the smaller tank. Again the top manway was removed and the product appeared stable inside the tank with no visible vapors or fumes escaping. They emptied this tank and did a triple rinse in the same manner as the outside tank with no issues. They stopped for lunch at 1:15 pm and discussed the afternoon activities because the outside scrubber
